{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Use Australian English|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox AFL biography | name = Jimmy Melbourne | image = | fullname = James Edward Melbourne | birth_date = c. 1876 | birth_place = [[York, Western Australia]] | death_date = 13 December 1937 | death_place = [[South Melbourne, Victoria]] | height = <!-- ### cm --> | weight = <!-- ### kg --> | position = | club1 = [[West Perth Football Club|West Perth]] | years1 = 1900–1901 | games_goals1 = 22 (5) | club2 = [[South Fremantle Football Club|South Fremantle]] | years2 = 1902 | games_goals2 = 4 | club3 = [[Subiaco Football Club|Subiaco]] | years3 = 1903–1904 | games_goals3 = | statsend = 1904 | careerhighlights = }}
'''James Edward Melbourne''' (''c.'' 1876 – 13 December 1937) was the first [[Indigenous Australian]] to play senior [[Australian rules football]] in a major Australian football league.<ref name="West">{{cite news|title=Hunting the ghost of greased lightning |publisher=West Australian Newspapers Limited|work=[[The West Australian]]|last=Wilson|first=Ray|date=5 September 2009|page=24}}</ref>
Melbourne was orphaned at the age of four and spent his formative years in a [[Middle Swan, Western Australia|Middle Swan]] [[orphanage]] before being put into the care of various businessmen in York.<ref name="West"/> As a teenager, he was an accomplished [[jockey]] and spent time in prison for petty crimes (including stealing, cashing a cheque, passing [[counterfeit]] coins, and escaping from a lock-up).<ref name="West"/>
Melbourne played his first game for [[West Perth Football Club|West Perth]] against [[East Fremantle Football Club|East Fremantle]] in the [[West Australian Football League|Western Australian Football Association]] (WAFL) on 2 June 1900 and was a member of their 1901 premiership side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=1-5545-0-0-0&sID=75916&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=5897893&sectionID=75916|title=WAFL Premierships|publisher=Sporting Pulse|accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> He then moved to [[South Fremantle Football Club|South Fremantle]] in 1902,<ref name="Bulldogs">{{cite web|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/sport/a/-/wafl/5701308/south-fremantle-bulldogs-announce-aboriginal-team-of-century/ |title=South Fremantle Bulldogs announce Aboriginal team of century |publisher=West Australian Newspapers Limited |work=[[The West Australian]]|date= 3 July 2009|accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref> playing four games,<ref>[http://www.southfremantlefc.com.au/assets/SFFC/SFFC-Indigenous-Players.pdf South Fremantle Football Club Indigenous League Players] Retrieved 26 July 2012.</ref> and then went to play for Subiaco in 1903 and 1904. In 1907, Melbourne played in the Collie Football Association, and then in the Bunbury Football Association until 1908. He was also a boxer and professional runner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xR0RAAAAIBAJ&sjid=MJcDAAAAIBAJ&dq=jimmy-melbourne&pg=7005%2C5672140 |title=Battered with axe|work=[[The Age]]|date=13 December 1937|accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref> In the later stages of his life he moved to [[Melbourne]], Victoria, and joined the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] at the outbreak of [[World War I]].<ref name="West"/>
On 13 December 1937, Melbourne was murdered at his home in [[South Melbourne, Victoria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2447408 |title=Battered to death |work=[[Canberra Times]]|date=13 December 1937 |accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2447491 |title=Aborigine's Death |work=[[Canberra Times]]|date=14 December 1937 |accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref> At this time he is recorded as being married or living with Mary Edith Melbourne, a former war nurse.<ref>The Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954) Friday 24 December 1937 p 10 Article</ref> His landlord was convicted of Melbourne's manslaughter and sentenced to five years in prison.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NTkTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K5cDAAAAIBAJ&dq=moore%20melbourne&pg=3781%2C5955732 |title=Gaol for five years|work=[[The Age]]|date=18 February 1938|accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref> Melbourne is buried at [[Springvale Botanical Cemetery]] in Melbourne.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://smct.org.au/deceasedsearch/result/59662 |title=James Edward Melbourne |publisher=Southern Metropolitan Cemeteries Trust}}</ref>
Since 2007, Melbourne's name has been perpetuated with the ''Jimmy Melbourne Cup'' being awarded to the winners of a game played between South Fremantle and [[Claremont Football Club|Claremont]] during [[NAIDOC|National Aboriginal Islander Day Observance Committee]] Week (known as ''NAIDOC Week'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wafootball.com.au/news-archive/396-wafl-naidoc-game-heads-non-afl-weekend-in-perth |title=WAFL NAIDOC game heads non-AFL weekend in Perth |publisher=[[Western Australian Football League|WAFL]] |date=2 July 2008 |accessdate=7 September 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313144847/http://wafootball.com.au/news-archive/396-wafl-naidoc-game-heads-non-afl-weekend-in-perth |archivedate=13 March 2011 |df= }}</ref> These are the two WAFL clubs that have featured the most Aboriginal players.<ref name="Bulldogs"/>
