{{Use American English|date=September 2014}}
{{Use MDY dates|date=February 2015}}
[[File:700UFCA Recon 08-12-2014.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Long Beach Jane Doe]], whose body was found in 1974. This murder case was solved 39 years after she was found, yet she remains unidentified.]]

In California, there are many murder victims in the category of [[unidentified decedent]]s, whose identities remain unknown. In most of these cases, their murderer has never been identified.

{{anchor|Los Angeles County John Doe}}

==Los Angeles County John Doe (1968)==

[[File:1968-01481 Reconstruction 002.jpg|thumb|150px|left|1968 Los Angeles County John Doe]]

The body of a black male was located on February 9, 1968 in Los Angeles, Los Angeles County, California. The victim was a young man, aged 15 to 20 when he was shot to death by police. The John Doe was tall, approximately six feet three inches tall and weighed 156 pounds with black hair and brown eyes. His frame was noticeably thin.<ref name="Crime Watch Daily">{{cite web | url=http://crimewatchdaily.com/2015/10/19/help-crime-watch-daily-and-carl-koppelman-give-names-to-these-5-murder-victims/ | title=HELP CRIME WATCH DAILY AND CARL KOPPELMAN GIVE NAMES TO THESE 5 MURDER VICTIMS | publisher=Fox | work=Crime Watch Daily | date=10 October 2015 | accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> He was wearing a green sweater over a green turtle neck shirt. Blue pants, a brown leather belt, green socks, white boxers and gray shoes were also worn by the decedent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 1391UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/1391umca.html|work=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Hacienda Heights John Doe}}

==Hacienda Heights John Doe==
[[File:1972-11771 (865UMCA) - Reconstruction 003.jpg|thumb|150px|Hacienda Heights John Doe]]

On the night of November 5, 1972, the body of a young man who was between eighteen and twenty-five years old was discovered in [[Hacienda Heights, California|Hacienda Heights]], Los Angeles County, California. The victim had suffered several gunshot wounds, which were previously heard by residents. He was found at the base of a ditch next to a road that had blood visible on it, which was likely his. The John Doe wore a denim jacket, brown boots, a pink shirt, bell bottoms and jeans with the words "love" and "peace" sewn on the legs, respectively. Jewelry worn by the decedent consisted of a gold-colored earring with a peace sign, and a white chained rosary bead necklace.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 3650|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/3650|work=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=2 October 2014|date=10 September 2008}}</ref> His brown or strawberry blond hair was long and his eyes were blue. He stood at six feet tall and weighed 175 pounds. He also may have worn a pair of yellow glasses found near his body. Apart from the image shown, his face has been reconstructed by the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 865UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/865umca.html|work=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Wilmington John Doe}}

==Wilmington John Doe==

[[File:1973-02574 Reconstruction 005.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Wilmington John Doe may have been a victim of [[Randy Steven Kraft]].]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184198c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

On February 5, 1973, the naked body of a young man, between 17 and 25 years old, was found in a ditch near a freeway in [[Wilmington, California]]. He was 5 feet 8 inches tall, and had a faint beard, medium-length brown hair, and a fair complexion. His hair and eyes were brown. He had type A blood.<ref name="Case File 1155UMCA">{{cite web|title=Case File 1155UMCA|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/1155umca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref> His teeth had had several fillings, meaning that he had received dental care. The victim had a number of thin, inch-long scars on the far end of his right leg.<ref name="John Doe 1973">{{cite web|title=John Doe 1973|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184198/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref> He had been strangled and had been sodomized with a brown [[sock]] one or two days prior. It is presumed that he was murdered by [[Randy Steven Kraft]], who was a [[serial killer]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Newton|first1=Michael|title=Randy Kraft, the Freeway Killer|url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/serial_killers/predators/kraft/4.html|website=crimelibrary.com|publisher=Crime Library|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>

==San Francisco County John Doe (1973)==
On December 24, 1973 a unknown homeless man was abducted and killed in San Francisco California during the [[Zebra murders]] of 1973-1974; all that was found of his remains were his torso minus head, arms and legs. {{sfn|Howard|1979|pp=166, 173–74, 180–01}}{{sfn|Talbot|2012|pp=213–14}}

==Long Beach Jane Doe==

{{main article|Long Beach Jane Doe}}

A young woman murdered in 1974. Her killer confessed to her murder in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Murder, Rape Suspect of 1974 Jane Doe to be Arraigned|url=http://www.randomlengthsnews.com/murder-rape-suspect-of-1974-jane-doe-to-be-arraigned/|accessdate=29 November 2014|work=Random Lengths News|date=11 June 2013}}</ref>

{{anchor|San Mateo County John Doe (1975)}}

==San Mateo County John Doe (1975)==

[[File:San Mateo John Doe 1975 Shoes.jpg|thumb|right|Boots worn by the San Mateo John Doe]]

The remains of a child aged nine to twelve were recovered on October 20, 1975, after an initial discovery on October 13 in a wooded area in Woodside, San Mateo County, California.<ref>{{cite web|title=JOHN DOE #75-936|url=http://coroner.smcgov.org/john-doe-75-936-0|website=coroner.smcgov.org|publisher=San Mateo County Coroner|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> The victim was determined to be white and was deceased between one and three years before his skeleton was found. The child was about four feet seven inches to five feet tall at an indeterminable weight. He likely did not have access to dental care, as many problems were noticed in his teeth. The body was found clothed with a pair of size seven to seven and a half boots and a blue, long-sleeved sweater and a crucifix made of wood were found near the remains.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Doe 1975|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1167344/1/screen|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> Additionally, rosary beads and a jacket liner with multicolored stripes were recovered.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 10524|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/10524|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=14 August 2012}}</ref> The body was initially believed to be that of an adult female until the victim was concluded to be a male around the age of eleven.<ref>{{cite news|title=Skeleton that of a Boy, 11|url=https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/19350|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=San Mateo Times|date=23 October 1975}}</ref> Signs of homicide were not initially found at first, although it was eventually discovered that the child died due to a fracture inflicted on the skull. It is speculated that the victim may have been a "migrant worker."<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 771UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/771umca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=23 October 2014}}</ref> Investigators appealed to the public for tips leading to the child's identification without success.<ref>{{cite news|title=Who Wore Rosary?|url=https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/19349|accessdate=2 July 2015|work=San Mateo Times|date=5 November 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Nipton Jane Doe}}

==Nipton Jane Doe==
[[File:Nipton Jane Doe 1976 Reconstruction 3.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Nipton Jane Doe]]

{{commons category|Nipton Jane Doe}}

The body of a white female between eighteen and thirty was found on May 30, 1976 near Nipton, San Bernardino County, California. She had died from a shotgun wound to her back and was then deposited in a mine shaft in the [[Mojave Desert]].<ref>{{cite web |title= HOMICIDE COLD CASE |url= http://cms.sbcounty.gov/Portals/34/HomicideColdCase/1976/JaneDoe.pdf |website= cms.sbcounty.gov |accessdate= 3 March 2015}}</ref> The victim was murdered approximately four to six days before and wore a blue swimsuit.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 2503|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/2503|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=8 December 2014|date=26 August 2008}}</ref> She was overweight, approximately 140 to 150 pounds at the height of five feet four inches tall. The victim's front teeth overlapped and none of her wisdom teeth were found. She is not believed to have given birth during her lifetime. She had auburn hair and had previously painted her fingernails pink or orange.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 778UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/778ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|San Diego County Jane Doe (1978)}}

==San Diego County Jane Doe (1978)==
[[File:San Diego County Jane Doe (1978).jpg|thumb|right|250px|The 1978 San Diego Jane Doe's right ear was smaller than her left, and she had a front tooth that was cracked in half.]]

The body of a girl between the ages of 14 and 18 years was discovered on the side of a road on February 14, 1978, in [[Otay, California]]. She had died two days prior. Her body was unrecognizable because it had been set on fire. The cause of her death was by poisoning and torture.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sklar|first1=Debbie L.|title=Sketch Released of 1978 'Jane Doe' Found Poisoned Valentine's Day in Chula Vista|url=http://timesofsandiego.com/crime/2014/10/02/sketch-released-1978-jane-doe-found-poisoned-valentines-day-chula-vista/|accessdate=9 December 2014|work=Times of San Diego|agency=Times of San Diego LLC|date=2 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=San Diego's Unsolved Cold Cases|work=NBC 7 San Diego|publisher=NBC|date=2 October 2014}}</ref> The kind of poison used has not been disclosed by investigators.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Repard|first1=Pauline|title=Tips sought in teen's 1978 poisoning death|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2014/oct/02/sheriffs-homicide-proctor-valley-teen-poison-death/|accessdate=9 December 2014|work=UT San Diego|agency=The San Diego Union-Tribune, LLC|publisher=MLIM|date=2 October 2014}}</ref>

Examination concluded that she was a white girl, between 5 feet and 5 feet 1 inch tall, weighing 85 to 90 pounds. Her eye color is presumed to have been brown, although the autopsy did not confirm the color. Her hair was brown and tied back with a [[rubber band]]. The victim had had her ears pierced. Her right ear was deformed and was smaller than her left ear, which was a distinctive feature.

She had had a [[root canal]] done on her bottom right front tooth, which was split into two pieces.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1978|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184501/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> Blueish overalls and a white [[Top (clothing)|top]] with blue flowers were the only clothing worn by the girl.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 857UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/857ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=9 December 2014|date=17 December 2007}}</ref>

Up to 1,000 dollars is being offered for information on the case.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who Murdered Jane Doe?|url=http://origin.library.constantcontact.com/download/get/file/1103305117625-549/092414+Jane+Doe.pdf|publisher=San Diego Crime Stoppers|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Long Beach John Doe (1978)}}

==Long Beach John Doe (1978)==

[[File:1978-06979 Reconstruction 003c.jpg|150px|thumb|left|An artist's drawing of what Long Beach John Doe may have looked like.]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184172c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

{{commons category|Long Beach John Doe (1978)}}

A white man, between 15 and 23 years old, was found on June 3, 1978, less than one day after his death in [[Long Beach, California]]. He had been strangled and left in a parking lot lying face down. His right hand had been stamped with the word "paid," possibly indicating that he had recently attended some sort of festival or party. His hair was brown. His eyes were [[Eye color#Hazel|hazel]]. He was about 5 feet 7 to 5 feet 11 inches tall and weighed between 130 and 145 pounds. Examiners stated that he had a scar above one of his eyebrows.<ref name="Case File 1392UMCA">{{cite web|title=Case File 1392UMCA|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/1392umca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="Unidentified Person Detail Page">{{cite web|title=Unidentified Person Detail Page|url=http://coroner.co.la.ca.us/htm/uipdetail.cfm?proc_flg=L&unid_case_num=1978-06979|publisher=Los Angeles County Coroner|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="John Doe 1978">{{cite web|title=John Doe 1978|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184172/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="John Doe -- 146">{{cite news|title=John Doe -- 146|url=http://www.presstelegram.com/technology/20120602/john-doe-146|accessdate=23 June 2014|agency=Press Telegram|date=1 June 2012}}</ref><ref name="Case Report - NamUs UP # 4428">{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 4428|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/full_report/4428|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>

Authorities do not believe he was a [[runaway (dependent)|runaway]] or a transient, as his clothing was of good quality. He wore running shoes, and all of his clothing was blue except for a brown belt. Some have speculated that he was a victim of serial killer [[Randy Steven Kraft]].<ref name="Crime Watch Daily"/>

{{anchor|Rancho Cucamonga Jane Doe}}

==Rancho Cucamonga Jane Doe==
{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1111328c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

[[File:Rancho Cucamonga Reconstruction 002a.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Reconstruction of the Rancho Cucamonga Jane Doe]]

{{commons category|Rancho Cucamonga Jane Doe}}

The body of a female between fifteen and thirty years old was discovered on June 7, 1979 in [[Rancho Cucamonga, California|Rancho Cucamonga]], [[San Bernardino County, California|San Bernardino County]], [[California]]. The victim was left at the edge of a vineyard and wore only green socks and Lower Quarter Earth brand leather boots.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1979|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1111328/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=27 October 2014}}</ref> The victim had been asphyxiated and beaten, then left face-down in the vineyard. It is believed that the Jane Doe was dead within days before her body was found.<ref>{{cite news|title=Woman's Body Found|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/62442223/?terms=woman%27s+body+found+rancho+cucamonga|accessdate=19 September 2017|page=28|work=San Bernardino Sun|date=8 June 1979}}{{subscription required}}</ref> She was approximately five feet two inches tall with shoulder-length light brown hair and weighed between 100 and 110 pounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 633UFCA|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/633ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=27 October 2014}}</ref> Her teeth overlapped somewhat and one of her teeth was mesially fractured. Forty-four missing people have been excluded from the case.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 2512|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/2512|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=27 October 2014|date=26 August 2008}}</ref>

==Riverside County Jane Doe (1980)==

[[File:Jane Doe 1980 CA.jpg|thumb|150px|Riverside County Jane Doe]]

The body of a Caucasian female aged twenty to twenty-five was found in a ravine in Riverside County, California on February 16, 1980.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 7139|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/7139|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=17 May 2015|date=10 March 2010}}</ref> The victim had died about a day or two before her discovery. Her height and weight were estimated to be five feet four inches and 120 pounds, respectively. She was found wearing a pair of blue pants, sandals and a tan, long sleeved blouse. Her hair was brown and short, presumed to have been cut recently. Her eyes were hazel and she had two scars on her right arm, one on the lower portion and another on the upper. The victim may have been of high socioeconomic status because of her high-quality clothes and that her fingernails were well cared for.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 600UFCA|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/600ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=17 May 2015}}</ref>

==Wilson Chouest victims==

{{Main|Wilson Chouest}}

Two women killed in July 1980 in Kern and Ventura Counties. Chouest was convicted in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=DNA Links Kidnapper, Rapist To 1980 Cold Case Murders In Ventura, Kern Counties|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/09/30/dna-links-kidnapper-rapist-to-1980-cold-case-murders-in-ventura-kern-counties/|accessdate=1 October 2015|work=CBS Los Angeles|publisher=CBS|date=30 September 2015}}</ref>

{{anchor|Newhall Jane Doe}}

==Newhall Jane Doe==

{{external media
| align  = 
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184175c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

On August 26, 1980, the remains of a girl, known as Jane Doe 18, were found in [[Newhall, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=People vs. Clark|url=http://online.ceb.com/calcases/C4/3C4t41.htm|website=|publisher=Los Angeles County Sheriff Department|accessdate=4 November 2014|date=30 July 1992}}</ref> The girl, between 15 and 20 years of age, had been shot in the back of the head two months to a year before she was found. It is believed that she was a victim of serial killer [[Doug Clark]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hot Case 775|url=http://doenetwork.org/hot/hotcase775.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>

The victim was white, with light brown to blond hair, and was 5 feet 4 to 5 feet 8 inches tall. Because of decomposition, her body was skeletonized. Consequently, her eye color and weight could not be determined. She was wearing a red sweatshirt and had one hoop earring, indicating that she had pierced ears. Four fillings in her teeth and evidence of a previous surgery were found.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1980|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184175/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>

Four missing women have been ruled out as a possible identity of the victim.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4370|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/4370|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=4 November 2014|date=10 September 2008}}</ref>

{{anchor|Newhall John Doe}}

==Newhall John Doe==

A day after his death, the body of a young man was found in the [[Angeles National Forest]] in [[Newhall, California]], on December 8, 1980. He was between 16 and 25 years of age and was 5 feet 4 to 5 feet 8 inches tall. He weighed 140 to 150 pounds. He may have been [[Hispanic]], as he had dark, curly hair and brown eyes. He had suffered severe wounds that disfigured his features, due to a gunshot to his head and four gunshots to his chest. He was fully clothed when found, wearing black boots, a beige, button-down shirt with matching pants, brown shorts, and white and green socks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 994UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/994umca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=17 December 2017|date=30 December 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|San Bernardino County John Doe (1983)}}

==San Bernardino County John Doe (1983)==

[[File:San Bernardino County John Doe (1983) Belt.jpg|thumb|left|130px|Harley Davidson belt buckle worn by the San Bernardino County John Doe, found in 1983.]]

{{external media
| align  = 
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184218c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

The body of a teen was discovered inside of a gondola car near Bloomington, San Bernardino County, California on June 20, 1983. The victim, a Hispanic male, aged fifteen to seventeen, was killed by gunshot wounds. A pay stub was found with the body, with the name Ernesto Carillo Aguilar, with the birth date of June 24, 1963. However, authorities could not verify if it was his actual name, which indicates he was using a false name and may have been an undocumented immigrant.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 2613|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/2613|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=17 August 2014|date=26 August 2008}}</ref> The clothing he wore included a white shirt containing the letters NYC with an apple shape, quite possibly a reference to [[New York City]]. He also wore loafer shoes and a belt with a brass [[Harley Davidson]] buckle.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 1292UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/1292umca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref> He was five feet eleven inches tall and weighed 146 pounds, with dark brown, straight hair and with scars on his hand, right arm and right shoulder. The victim had been deceased within a day before his discovery.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Doe 1983|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184218/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref>

==Crescenta Valley Jane Doe==

{{Commons category|Crescenta Valley Jane Doe}}

[[File:LA 1983 Jane Doe necklace.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Necklace worn by the Crescenta Valley Jane Doe]]

On June 26, 1983, the burned body of a Caucasian female between sixteen and twenty-eight years of age was found inside of an abandoned mobile home, also burned, in Crescenta Valley, Los Angeles County, California.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4273|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/4273|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=2 July 2015|date=10 September 2008}}</ref> The victim had died less than two hours before her remains were found, yet the body was not recognizable because it had been set afire. Her hair was determined to have been straight and blond and her eyes were brown. The victim's height and weight could not be estimated, but it is believed she was of petite build and at a small height. The victim wore a square pendant on a gold chain and a gold watch.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1983|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1106246/1/screen|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref> The female was strangled with wire and had been sexually assaulted with a hose, which was still present in the vaginal cavity. A suspect was arrested for her murder and was subsequently convicted. He had allegedly picked the female up earlier that day, sometime in the morning, and also stated he had beaten the victim.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 588UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/588ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=2 July 2015}}</ref>

{{anchor|Los Angeles County Jane Doe (1985)}}

==Los Angeles County Jane Doe (1985)==
{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184450c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

An African-American infant's decomposing body was found on August 19, 1985 in an alley in Los Angeles, Los Angeles County, California.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4197|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/4197|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=8 January 2015|date=10 September 2008}}</ref> The child, a girl, was no more than a year old. She was extremely malnourished, which indicated she had been neglected by her caretakers. The girl was two feet two inches tall and weighed fourteen pounds at the time of her death. Her hair and eyes were brown and she had four teeth, which were the central incisors. Despite her severe neglect, both of her ears had been pierced.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1985|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184450/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref> The baby died from pneumonia and her death was ruled a homicide based on the signs of neglect.<ref>{{cite web|title=1221UFCA|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/1221ufca.html|accessdate=24 March 2018|work=[[The Doe Network]]|date=22 February 2009}}</ref>

{{anchor|Santa Clarita Does}}

==Santa Clarita Does==
{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184148c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction of  victim]
}}

On January 8, 1986, partial human [[skeletal]] remains were located in the Santa Clarita Valley, Los Angeles County, California.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unknown Doe |url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184148/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref> The decedent is believed to have been female, although the victim may have been male and died between 1985 and 1986. The age of the person was between thirteen and seventeen, although through a dental examination, could have been as old as twenty-two. The person's race may have been Asian or Hispanic, with black hair, standing at four feet nine inches to four feet eleven inches.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 4179|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/full_report/4179|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=16 August 2014|date=10 September 2008}}</ref> No traces of dental work were found in the mouth.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 969UFCA|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/969ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref>

A second victim's skull was located near the same area on July 26, 1987. Unlike the previous victim, the skull was positively determined to be that of a female. She had dental fillings present in her teeth and was between thirty and sixty years old. The cause of her death could be due to decapitation. No other remains were ever located.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 970UFCA|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/970ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 4114|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/4114|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=16 August 2014|date=10 September 2008}}</ref>

{{anchor|San Mateo County Jane Doe}}

==San Mateo County Jane Doe==
{{Double image|left|Daly City Doe 4c.jpg|100|Daly City Jane Doe 003.jpg|100|Reconstructions of the San Mateo County Jane Doe}}

{{Commons category|San Mateo County Jane Doe}}

On January 11, 1987, the body of a white female, locally known as Jane Doe 87-37, was located in Daly City, San Mateo County, California. Her body was disposed of on the side of a road, underneath a group of bushes and was discovered by two children riding bicycles.<ref name=jose>{{cite news|last1=Brannen|first=Johnny|title=Overdose Victim's Identity Still Unknown|url=https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/19299|accessdate=14 September 2014|agency=San Jose Mercury News|date=1997}}</ref> A number of pills, [[imipramine]] and desimpramine, were found in her body, which she also overdosed on.<ref name=doenetsan>{{cite web|title=Case File: 439UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/439ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Although she was strangled, her face had evidence of bruising, she had a cut lip and there were no signs that she used drugs, authorities concluded that she was likely force-fed the medication. The victim was around five feet three inches, 95 to 105 pounds and was approximately twenty-five to thirty years old when she died. She may have carried a child in the past and evidence was present that she had an [[appendectomy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 9938|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/9938|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]}}</ref> She had straight, dark brown hair and brown eyes, her right eye may have had a [[cataract]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Help Needed to Identify Deceased Person|url=https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/19300|website=identifyus.org|publisher=San Mateo County Coroner|accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The clothing the victim wore consisted of a hooded gray jacket with fleece lining, a hooded purple sweatshirt, a pair of brown and white socks, brown shoes and jeans.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unsolved Crimes |url= http://www.dalycity.org/City_Hall/Departments/police_department/news_room/unsolved_crimes.htm|website= www.dalycity.org |publisher= Daly City Police Department |accessdate= 14 September 2014 }}</ref> The shoes the victim wore were believed to have been expensive, despite the fact that she may have been a transient. She wore no jewelry, had no observable dental work, had not shaved underneath her arms or her legs and had dandruff on her scalp. Two packs of cigarettes were found with the body, one of which was full. Before she died, the Jane Doe was seen at a diner, where she purchased the cigarettes, and was witnessed arguing with a man by bystanders across the street. Although the woman's face was recognizable and her DNA, fingerprints and dental information were recovered, she was never identified.<ref name=doenetsan/> Those interviewed by police who had seen the victim had no idea who she was. Several missing people from the area that matched her description were eventually found alive.<ref name=jose/> In 2011, Daly City police noted similarities between the murder of Jane Doe and the modus operandi of serial killer [[Joseph Naso]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_19300480 |title=Police looking for serial killer link to Daly City cold case slaying |author=Melvin, Joshua |date=9 November 2011 |newspaper=San Jose Mercury News |accessdate=18 November 2015 }}</ref>

{{anchor|San Bernardino County Jane Doe (1987)}}

==San Bernardino County Jane Doe (1987)==

[[File:321UFCA Reconstruction 002a.jpg|thumb|left|150px|1987 San Bernardino Jane Doe]]

The body of a white female with a fair complexion between forty-five and fifty-five years old was located on June 19, 1987 in Colton, San Bernardino County, California.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 321UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/321ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=8 December 2014|date=6 February 2012}}</ref> The woman had been shot to death mere hours before her body was found. The victim had short hair that was originally auburn, but was dyed blond and it is believed that she had hazel eyes. She had two moles on her face, one on her right temple and another on the right side of her nose, which was fairly noticeable. Other distinct features the woman had included scars on her wrist, abdomen, and one near each knee. She was approximately five feet one inch and weighed between 132 and 135 pounds. She wore blue pajamas and stud earrings made from a yellow metal. The woman also wore a partial denture on her upper set of teeth.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 5997|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/5997|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=8 December 2014|date=6 October 2009}}</ref>

{{anchor|Van Nuys Jane Doe}}

== Van Nuys Jane Doe ==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/452UFCA.jpg Sketch]
}}

The body of a woman between twenty-four and thirty-three years old was discovered in Van Nuys, Los Angeles County, California on July 21, 1987. Her body was wrapped in a tarp and some blankets. The body was found weeks afterward. The victim had been strangled and had her arms severed at the elbows, preventing analysis of fingerprints. She had brown hair and eyes, had braces at one time in her life and also had some missing teeth and fillings in her mouth. She wore what appeared to be a handmade dress, a bra, [[Slip (clothing)|slip]], underwear and mismatched shoes, one being a high heel and the other an open toed shoe.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4117|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/4117|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=23 February 2015|date=10 September 2008}}</ref> The female was about five feet eight inches tall and was at a weight between 110 and 120 pounds. Further physical examination indicated she had been pregnant at one point in life and had consumed cocaine before her murder. It is possible that this case may be linked to serial killings in the area, but authorities are unsure. The female's body was eventually cremated.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 452UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/452ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>

{{anchor|Anaheim Jane Doe}}

==Anaheim Jane Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/7660/Images/29366/Original NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/7660/Images/29362/Original Side]
}}

[[File:Anaheim sketch.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Contemporary [[facial composite|composite drawing]] of Anaheim Jane Doe]]

The extensively decomposed remains of a young female were found at the side of a [[freeway]] in the [[Santa Ana Canyon]] in [[Anaheim, California|Anaheim]], [[Orange County, California|Orange County]] on August 30, 1987. The victim's body had almost completely [[Skeletonization|skeletonized]] at the time of discovery, although some fragments of soft tissue were still present upon the remains. The victim—also known as Jane Doe 87-04092 EL—was a slender young woman who had medium length light hair; she was likely between 15 and 19 years old when she died,<ref>{{cite news|title=Remains in Canyon are that of a Woman|url=http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v247/suzannec4444/Tammy/Orangecounty1a.jpg|accessdate=2 October 2014|agency=Anaheim Bulletin|date=1 September 1987}}</ref> and may possibly have been a teenage runaway.<ref>{{cite news|title=Remains in Canyon are that of a Woman|url=http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v247/suzannec4444/Tammy/OrangeCounty3.jpg|accessdate=2 October 2014|agency=Anaheim Bulletin|date=1 September 1987}}</ref>

At the crime scene, enough hair was found with the body to determine that the girl had [[blond]] or light brown hair, although no personal belongings beyond a red handkerchief were discovered with her remains. Her skull was [[forensic facial reconstruction|reconstructed]] by Shannon Collis in hopes of identifying the body, determining she also had high [[Zygomatic bone|cheekbones]]. One of her front teeth was slightly chipped, while three of her other teeth had visible cavities, and six molars were missing. She was estimated to be between five feet one to five feet four inches tall. It is believed that the victim had died around six weeks before her body was discovered, meaning she likely died in July 1987. She may possibly have died by repeated stab wounds to her chest area, as incisive damage to two of her ribs suggested.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Needham|first1=John|title=ID-ing the Dead : Bodies of John and Jane Does Trigger Special Concern Among 34 Members of Coroner's Office|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-08-17/news/li-996_1_deputy-coroner|accessdate=6 October 2014|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=17 August 1989}}</ref> Therefore, her death was ruled as a definite homicide.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Eddy|first1=Steve|title=3D Techniques may ID dead Teen-Ager: Skull of girl found in canyon used in OC's first facial reconstruction|url=http://www.img.photobucket.com/albums/v247/suzannec4444/Tammy/Orangecountya.jpg|accessdate=2 October 2014|agency=Orange County Register|date=26 October 1987}}</ref><ref name="Bishop">{{cite web| last=Bishop| first=Alex| title=Unsolved Murder Spotlight: The Orange County Jane Doe| url=http://www.crimelibrary.com/blog/2013/05/30/unsolved-murder-spotlight-the-orange-county-jane-doe/index.html| publisher=Crimelibrary.com| accessdate=16 April 2014| date=30 May 2013}}</ref><ref name="icaremissingpersonscoldcases.yuku.com">{{cite web| title=Unidentified Jane Doe in 1987 in Aneheim California|url=http://icaremissingpersonscoldcases.yuku.com/topic/765/Unidentified-Jane-Doe-in-1987-in-Aneheim-California#.U1FaefldXTo| accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref><ref name="Case File 22UFCA">{{cite web| title=Case File 22UFCA| url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/22ufca.html| publisher=[[The Doe Network]]| accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref><ref name="Jane Doe 1987">{{cite web| title=Jane Doe 1987| url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184201| publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]| accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref> In 2018, the [[DNA Doe Project]] took on Anaheim Jane Doe's case. Their search for her identity is ongoing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Anaheim Jane Doe |url=http://dnadoeproject.org/case/anaheim-jane-doe/ |website=DNA Doe Project |accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref>

==Los Angeles County John Doe (1987)==

[[File:John Doe 1987 LA retouched.jpg|thumb|1987 Los Angeles County John Doe]]

A Hispanic man was found stabbed to death on November 22, 1987 in Los Angeles, Los Angeles County, California. He had been left on a sidewalk after his murder, which occurred on the same day. The victim was between twenty-five and thirty-five years of age, had brown eyes and black hair. Examiners concluded he was approximately five feet seven inches tall and weighed 130 pounds. DNA and dental information for the victim were never recorded, although his fingerprints were taken and are entered in national databases.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 2611UMCA|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/2611umca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=3 July 2015|date=18 April 2015}}</ref> The victim had no distinct markers of identification except for a scar on his right arm.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4107|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/4107|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=3 July 2015|date=10 September 2008}}</ref>

{{anchor|Santa Ana Jane Doe (1988)}}

==Santa Ana Jane Doe (1988)==

[[File:1988 Santa Ana Jane Doe.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Sketch of the 1988 Santa Ana Jane Doe]]

{{commons category|Santa Ana Jane Doe (1988)}}

A Hispanic woman's body was found on March 31, 1988 in Santiago Park, Santa Ana, Orange County, California.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 24UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/24ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=The Doe Network|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref> Her death was by murder, as she had been stabbed multiple times in the face and once in the neck and later decapitated with the sawing motion of a blade.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cold-case mysteries that have withstood the test of time|url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/police-628068-woman-dna.html|accessdate=11 January 2015|work=Orange County Register|date=5 July 2014}}</ref> The body was discovered first, lacking a head. When investigators later returned to the site after four days, the head was located, believed to have been placed there after the body was removed. She was Hispanic, possibly native to the southwestern part of the country or Mexico, judging by an examination of her teeth. The victim was a young woman, presumed to be between twenty-two and twenty-eight years old, although she could have been as young as twenty. The body was clothed, with a yellow sweater, white pants, white shoes. She may have had a [[laparoscopy]], as a scar was located on her stomach.<ref>{{cite web|title=88-01828-SC|url=http://ocsd.org/divisions/prof/coroner/ud/jane/8801828sc|website=ocsd.org|publisher=Orange County Police Department|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref> She was estimated to be between five feet three inches to five feet five inches tall at a weight of 130 pounds. She had nine-inch long black hair.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orange California Jane Doe March 1988|url=http://www.canyouidentifyme.org/OrangeCaliforniaJaneDoeMarch1988|website=canyouidentifyme.org|accessdate=11 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 7663|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/7663|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=11 January 2015|date=26 August 2010}}</ref> The case was reopened in April 2015, in hopes to identify the victim and solve her murder.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Greg|title=SANTA ANA DETECTIVES REOPEN 1988 COLD CASE TO IDENTIFY 'JANE DOE,' FIND KILLER|url=http://abc7.com/news/santa-ana-detectives-reopen-1988-cold-case-to-identify-jane-doe/690140/|accessdate=18 February 2016|work=ABC 7 Eyewitness News|publisher=ABC|date=30 April 2015}}</ref>

{{anchor|Los Angeles County Jane Doe (1989)}}

==Los Angeles County Jane Doe (1989)==
[[File:1989-05825 Reconstruction 6c.jpg|thumb|150px|left|1989 Los Angeles County Jane Doe illustrated with curly hair]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184145c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

A Hispanic female, who suffered trauma to the head, was found lying on her back, deceased, in an alley on May 25, 1989 in Los Angeles, Los Angeles County, California. The girl was believed to be between the ages of twelve and fifteen when she died hours before her discovery due to an undisclosed cause. The height and weight of the female were estimated to be five feet three inches and 124 pounds, respectively. Her hair was either black or dark brown and her eyes were also brown. The texture of her hair is disputed, as some sources state she had curly hair and others claim it was straight.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1989|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184145/1/screen|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref> Despite her young age, she had multiple tattoos: an "oval or diamond" shaped design around the letters "p," "o," "h" and "s" along with another on the back her upper right leg.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 3979|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/3979|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=7 July 2015|date=10 September 2008}}</ref> The tattoos were hard to read and probably homemade.<ref name="Case File 484UFCA">{{cite web|title=Case File 484UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/484ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=7 July 2015}}</ref> The girl wore a blue shirt that read "Somebody in California Loves Me," dark blue but faded jeans, a tan bra, white or green underwear, white socks and black shoes with some red. She also wore jewelry that included a ring with a lion decoration, a ring with a light blue stone along with earrings, a bracelet adorned with pendants and a necklace.<ref name="Case File 484UFCA"/>

{{anchor|Placer County Jane Doe}}

==Placer County Jane Doe==

{{external media
| align  = 
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1103877c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1103877x1.jpg Necklace]
}}

On February 10, 1990, a young woman's body was found by two men in [[Colfax, California|Colfax]], [[Placer County, California]]. She was between sixteen and twenty-six years old at the time of her death, which is believed to have occurred while she was hiking, three to six months before.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 632|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/6325|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=29 November 2014|date=9 December 2009}}</ref> She was around four feet ten to five foot three inches with an estimated weight range of 120 to 150 pounds, at an average or overweight build. She could have been biracial, of white and Hispanic ancestry and she had dark brown hair with a reddish tint. Her jewelry included three earrings on her left ear and a pearl necklace, along with two mother of pearl rings. She may have been [[diabetes|diabetic]], as two insulin syringes were found near the corpse.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1990|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1103877/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref> A presumably homemade tattoo was found on her chest of a cross and she had two scars, possibly from removing cysts from her lower back and right breast. The victim wore blue shorts, a sleeveless shirt and a pair of new sneakers, which were white. Her cause of death is unknown but is suspected to be homicide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 114UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/114ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Solano County Jane Doe}}

==Solano County Jane Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/63UFCA2.jpg 3D reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/63UFCA1.jpg Sketch]
}}
On April 26, 1991, the body of a woman was found lying face-up in Vacaville, Solano County, California. The victim had died from some sort of asphyxia, either by strangulation or suffocation. She was twenty-five to thirty-five years old and was approximately five feet five inches tall. She is presumed to be white with Native American characteristics and had long hair that was brownish-blond. Although she was too decomposed to determine eye color, her fingerprints were obtained along with her dental information and DNA. She had fillings and five missing teeth, but three of them had been lost after her death. She was wearing a long-sleeved dress that was dark along with a sweater and a blue tank top, with a wool cap. No other clothing was found, except for a jacket covering the body and her dress had been pulled above her waist, indicating she was sexually assaulted. A ring with a green stone and a watch with a silver-colored face were also worn by the victim. Her body was exhumed in 1998. Along with wearing a large amount of clothing, the victim's legs were not shaved, possibly indicating she was a transient.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 63UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/63ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|San Diego County John Doe (1991)}}

==San Diego County John Doe (1991)==

[[File:1375UCMAd.jpg|thumb|150px|The San Diego County John Doe may have been native to Vietnam]]

A young man was struck in the back of his head with a two-by-four on September 8, 1991 in San Diego, California. The man died later that day. He was between seventeen and twenty-nine years old and was five feet eight inches at a weight of 112 pounds. He had dark hair and brown eyes and may have spoken to doctors in Vietnamese, although it is not certain if this was true. At the time of death, he wore a long-sleeved shirt with a plaid design and a white undershirt. It has not been published if he wore anything other than these two garments.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 1375UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/1375umca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 4948|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/4948|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=23 September 2014|date=17 March 2009}}</ref>

{{anchor|Los Angeles County Jane Doe (1991)}}

==Los Angeles County Jane Doe (1991)==

[[File:1991-08384 Reconstruction 001d.jpg|thumb|left|150px|1991 Los Angeles County Jane Doe]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184173c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

On September 11, 1991, the body of a Hispanic female was located in the Green Meadows Park in Los Angeles, Los Angeles County, California, hours after her death. The victim was between fifteen and twenty years of age at the time of her murder and was five feet two inches at a weight of 170 pounds when she died. The girl had wavy dark brown to black hair reaching past her shoulders and had brown eyes. After examining her teeth, it was discovered that one of her upper teeth had an infection that would likely be painful, which may have caused visible distress to the Jane Doe.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1991|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184173/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref> The victim's skin on her abdomen had areas with different colors, possibly indicating that she had [[vitiligo]]. Clothing found at the scene consisted of a white shirt with blue stripes, shorts made from denim, a white bra, socks and hiking boots reaching the ankles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unidentified Person Detail|url=http://mec.lacounty.gov/wps/portal/mec/main/home/caseinformation/unidentifiedpersondetail?unidentified=1&getPic=1&CaseNum=1991-08384|website=mec.lacounty.gov|publisher=Los Angeles County Coroner|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref> Marks and tan lines near her eyes indicated that she may have worn some sort of eyeglasses before her death.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 443UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/443ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref> Scars on her body included ones on her collar bone, right lower leg and on her left knee.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 3838|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/3838|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=10 December 2014|date=10 September 2008}}</ref>

{{anchor|Los Angeles County John Does (1992)}}

==Los Angeles County John Does (1992)==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184146c2.jpg NCMEC reconstruction of older victim]
| image2 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184146c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction of younger victim]
}}

[[File:UP 3773 and UP 3774 (1400UMCA and 1397UMCA) Reconstruction 001.jpg|left|thumb|The Los Angeles County John Does may have died after participating in a gang exercise.]]

Two Hispanic teenage boys were shot at a bus stop on July 19, 1992. The older victim, estimated to be between seventeen and nineteen years old, wore a T-shirt, jeans and tennis shoes and had a scar on both of his thighs and one of his hips. The boy also had a small amount of facial hair and had a darker complexion than his companion. He stood at five feet six inches and weighed 170 pounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 3773|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/3773|website=namus.gov|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 1400UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/1400umca.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Doe 1992|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184146/2#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> His age was initially believed to have been between thirteen and sixteen.<ref>{{cite web|title=1992-06614|url=http://coroner.co.la.ca.us/htm/uipdetail.cfm?proc_flg=L&unid_case_num=1992-06614|publisher=Los Angeles County Coroner|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> The other victim was between fourteen and seventeen years old and was of the same height, but weighed 128 pounds; his hair was somewhat longer than the other victim. He wore jeans and tennis shoes, like the older male, but wore a [[Casio]] watch and a scar was observable on one of his forearms. This victim died the same day he was found, but the other lived until July 20.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 1397UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/1397umca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Doe 1992|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184146/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> His original age estimation was between twelve and sixteen.<ref>{{cite web|title=1992-06560|url=http://coroner.co.la.ca.us/htm/uipdetail.cfm?proc_flg=L&unid_case_num=1992-06560|publisher=Los Angeles County Coroner|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> The two males allegedly died after a gang initiation took place.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 3774|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/3774|website=namus.gov|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Los Angeles County Jane Doe (1992)}}

==Los Angeles County Jane Doe (1992)==
{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184155c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184155x1.jpg Profile]
}}

On December 9, 1992, the body of a Hispanic female was discovered inside of several trash bags in [[South Central Los Angeles]], Los Angeles County, California. Despite being four feet six inches tall, her age was estimated to between fourteen and twenty-five years old. She wore a white shirt and skirt, two silver-colored rings on her right hand, a black belt, a purple slip and was found barefoot. She was of medium complexion and build, weighing 127 pounds. The cause of her death was multiple stab wounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 3761|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/3761|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 155UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/155ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1992|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184155/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref>

==Happy Face Killer victims==

{{main article|Keith Hunter Jesperson}}

Three women, presumably prostitutes, who were possibly killed by Keith Hunter Jesperson during August 1992 and September 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 497UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/497ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Riverside County Jane Doe}}

==Riverside County Jane Doe (1994)==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/5954 Sketch]
}}
On October 24, 1994, the body of a white female was found near Thousand Palms, Riverside County, California. She was elderly, at an age between sixty-five and eighty years old upon the time of her murder. She had been wrapped in plastic that was then secured with a brown cord that was partially concealed in the sand at the scene. The woman was approximately five feet four inches tall, although her weight could not be estimated due to decomposition. The woman had no teeth, but had worn dentures that were found with her body. However, these did not assist with the investigation as they lacked a brand name or a serial number. The woman wore blue shorts, a red shirt and a pair of underwear, but no shoes. She had brown and gray short hair and an eleven-inch scar on her abdomen that had healed.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 100UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/100ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=4 December 2014}}</ref> She also suffered from [[Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]] and [[Arteriosclerotic heart disease]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 7040|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/7040|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=4 December 2014|date=28 April 2010}}</ref>

{{anchor|San Joaquin County Jane Doe}}

==San Joaquin County Jane Doe==

[[File:San Joaquin County Jane Doe charm2.jpg|thumb|left|One of the charms found with the body of the San Joaquin County Jane Doe]]

{{commons category|San Joaquin County Jane Doe}}

The body of a woman was found on March 29, 1995 in Holt, San Joaquin County, California inside of a refrigerator bound with rope near a road. She had been murdered by a blow to the head with a blunt object around a year before she was found. The body was covered with a sleeping bag as well as a quilt. She was twenty-nine to forty-one years old and was five feet five to five feet seven inches at a weight of 110 to 130 pounds. She was white with strawberry-blond hair, had manicured nails and jewelry, including a wedding ring. She also possibly wore a charm necklace, as remnants of a leather band were located in her pocket. She wore a blue sweatshirt, denim shorts, a tee shirt, a bra, knee-high socks with various colors and expensive boots. It is believed that the refrigerator with her remains originated from elsewhere in California and likely floated along a levee to the location it was found.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 320UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/320ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Santa Clara County John Does}}

==Santa Clara County John Does==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/125UMCA.jpg Sketch of first victim]
| image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/126UMCA.jpg 3D reconstruction of second victim]
}}

The bodies of two Hispanic men were discovered in July 1997 in Gilroy, Santa Clara County, California. The first victim's torso was found severely decomposed on July 16; his skull was also later found. He was between thirty and fifty years of age. His clothing included a Nike shirt and jeans. A second man was found on July 31 and was fifteen to forty years old. Both men were between five feet five and five feet seven inches and may have been killed by asphyxiation. It is also believed that they were disposed of in a sewer line, which lead to the Gilroy Sewage Treatment Plant. They may have been native to Mexico and could have been involved in the drug trade. They likely were murdered on the same day, up to a year prior.<ref name="Case File 125UMCA">{{cite web|title=Case File 125UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/125umca.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref><ref name="Case File 126UMCA">{{cite web|title=Case File 126UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/126umca.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|San Diego County Jane Doe (1999)}}

{{anchor|Clarsburg John Doe}}

==Clarksburg John Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/275UMCA.jpg 3D reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/275UMCA5.jpg Second 3D reconstruction]
| image3 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/275umca.html Shirt]
}}

In Clarksburg, Yolo County, California, a man's body was found on March 4, 1999. He was a victim of homicide, as he was stabbed in the chest. He was killed months before his remains were found, which were so badly decomposed that his race was not possible to estimate. He was fully clothed and placed underneath a sleeping bag next to the Elk Slough estuary. He was between twenty and thirty-five years old and stood around five feet eleven inches tall at a weight of 182 pounds. His clothing included a tee shirt with a green "M," white and blue shoes and a green pair of boxers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 275UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/275umca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref>

==San Diego County Jane Doe (1999)==

[[File:345UFCA Reconstruction 003.jpg|thumb|150px|left|San Diego County Jane Doe]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/345UFCA.jpg Digital reconstruction]
}}

The body of a Hispanic female was located on August 11, 1999 in Oceanside, San Diego County, California. The victim was between fifteen and thirty-four years old and was between five feet one to five feet three inches tall at a weight of 135 to 143 pounds, having black hair and brown eyes.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 11738|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/11738|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=30 November 2014|date=5 November 2013}}</ref> She was killed by a blow to the head at an unknown location and was then transported to a drainage ditch where her body was then disposed of. She wore a green turtle-neck shirt, blue pants, white socks and white and blue Reebok sneakers. The victim wore her dark and wavy hair in a long braid. She was the mother of at least one child, giving birth a year or less prior to her death. A six-inch scar was found on the outside of her left knee, indicating she had had some sort of surgery in the past.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 345UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/345ufca.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Sacramento County Jane Doe}}

==Sacramento County Jane Doe==

[[File:Sacramento County Jane Doe teeth.jpg|left|150px|thumb|Sacramento County Jane Doe's teeth]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1107101c1.jpg Updated rendering of Sacramento County Jane Doe]

}}

The burning body of a black female aged sixteen to thirty (most likely between eighteen and twenty-four), was found in a dumpster in Sacramento, Sacramento County, California on June 29, 2001. The victim was discovered to have been alive at the time the fire was set, as damage in her airways indicated. Her hair color and eye color remain unknown, although they may have been dark in color.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 328UFCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/328ufca.html|work=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> She was previously believed to be white, until DNA analysis by the [[Parabon Nanolabs]] indicated she was of primarily African descent with some European ancestry. The testing also indicated her hair may have been black and her eyes could have been brown or hazel.
Her teeth were very well cared for. She had no known cavities at the time of death and had many plastic sealants and porcelain caps on her teeth. She presumably had braces at one point (or she had been prepared for them) and her wisdom teeth were present, two had not emerged.<ref>{{cite web|title=ARCHIVE FOR THE 'UNIDENTIFIED PEOPLE' CATEGORY|url=http://stillunsolved.wordpress.com/category/unidentified-people/page/2/|publisher=Wordpress|accessdate=28 November 2014|date=11 November 2012}}</ref> Her body, found wearing only jeans, was wrapped in a comforter and was then set ablaze when disposed of.<ref name="Jane Doe 2001">{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 2001|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1107101/1|work=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> The killer may have owned an orange Datsun car, which was seen leaving the scene before she was found.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 2367|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/2367|work=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=25 November 2014}}</ref> She had broken her nose at one point in her life. She was between five feet to five feet six inches tall and at a weight between 90 and 140 pounds. She was between a slender to average build when alive.<ref name="Jane Doe 2001"/>

{{anchor|Baby Doe}}

=="Baby Doe"==
{{for|the girl found in 2015|Bella Bond murder case}}

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/974UMCA.jpg Digital reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/974UMCA1.jpg Age progression]
}}

About ten days after he was suffocated, an infant's body was located on a recycling [[conveyor belt]] on February 10, 2004 in [[Stanton, California]]. He was likely killed on the day he was born, as his placenta and umbilical cord had not yet been severed from his body. A towel was found nearby with blood on it, which may have been used during the birth and, later, to murder the infant. A newspaper and a plastic bag were also found at the scene. The victim's ethnic background was difficult to determine, but he may have been African-American or Hispanic. His hair was black and curly, and his eyes were gray.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 974UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/974umca.html|work=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>

Although he had been dead for over a week, his body was not badly decomposed; his face was still recognizable.<ref>{{cite web|date=29 August 2013|work=National Missing and Unidentified Persons System|title=NamUs UP # 11561|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/11561|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>
{{anchor|Yermo John Doe}}

==Yermo John Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/757 NCMEC reconstruction]
}}
The burning body of a man aged twenty-five to forty was found near a road on May 8, 2006 in Yermo, San Bernardino County, California. He was presumed to have died approximately one to three hours prior to his discovery. He was a white or Hispanic male at a height of five feet seven inches and a weight of around 140 pounds. Due to the amount of time his remains were on fire, little clothing survived and his features could not be recognized. However, his DNA, fingerprints and dental information were obtainable.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 918|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/918|work=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=19 November 2014|date=12 March 2008}}</ref> Although he was an adult, two of his teeth had not yet emerged.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 1092UMCA|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/1092umca.html|work=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Irvine Jane Doe}}

==Irvine Jane Doe==

[[File:Irvine, CA Jane Doe.jpg|thumb|150px|left|The Irvine Jane Doe was six feet tall at the age of thirteen to twenty-six.]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1197905c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

{{commons category|Irvine Jane Doe}}

In Irvine, Orange County, California, the partially burned body of an African-American female was found on September 5, 2009 in a Pasternack Enterprises parking lot. The victim died less than a day before she was found; her face had not been damaged from the flames and her fingerprints, DNA and dental information were all recovered. She was tall at the age of thirteen to twenty-six, at six feet tall at a weight of 152 pounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=09-07236-RA|url=http://ocsd.org/divisions/prof/coroner/ud/jane/0907236ra|website=ocsd.org|publisher=Orange County Police Department|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref> The victim wore a pair of animal-print shorts, a black shirt and distinct high-heels that had a zipper in the front. She also may have worn a black bra, which was burned. She had brown eyes and short to medium-length curly, dark hair. Twenty-nine missing people have been ruled out as the decedent.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 7693|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/7693|work=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=10 December 2014|date=26 August 2010}}</ref>  Her face was reconstructed by the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children, although the reconstruction erroneously illustrated the girl with shoulder-length hair.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 2009|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1197905/1#poster|work=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=10 December 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|San Bernardino Jane Doe (2010)}}

==San Bernardino Jane Doe (February 2010)==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1141616c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/9413 Second NCMEC reconstruction]
}}

[[File:Barstow Backpack.jpg|thumb|left|Backpack containing the head of the 2010 San Bernardino County Jane Doe]]

In Barstow, San Bernardino County, California, the severed head of a Hispanic female was found concealed in a backpack on February 10, 2010 on the side of a road. She was between fourteen and nineteen years old with brown eyes and brown, straight hair that was shoulder length. Because her head was all that was located, her fingerprints as well as height and weight information could not be obtained. She had died days before, but was not recognizable due to the injuries she sustained.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 6718|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/6718|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=8 January 2015|date=22 February 2010}}</ref> Through examination, it was found that she had many dental fillings and had received very good dental care, possibly indicating she lived in a high socioeconomic class.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 2010|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1141616/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref>

==Mendocino County John Doe (2012)==

For years, a [[Humboldt County, California|Humboldt County]] CA family kayaked past a half-buried white tennis shoe on the bank of the [[Eel River (California)|Eel River]]. One of their trips occurred on October 30, 2012. When the family noted a second shoe protruding near the first, the father investigated. When he pulled one of the [[Payless ShoeSource|Pro Wing]] shoes from the dirt, a foot came with it. The family then called the [[Mendocino County, California|Mendocino County]] Sheriff's Department to the site, the 83000 block of Hwy 271, [[Piercy, California|Piercy]], CA.<ref name=shoe1>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Linda|title=Slow progress identifying human remains found in October
|url=http://www.willitsnews.com/general-news/20130314/slow-progress-identifying-human-remains-found-in-october|accessdate=24 July 2016|work=Willits News|date=14 March 2013}}</ref>

Once a Halloween prank was ruled out, the skeletal remains were deemed a homicide and were examined by [[CSU Chico]]'s Human Identification Laboratory. The remains were determined to be have been buried for several years; they were of a white male 25 to 45 years old, with a stature of 5 feet 11 inches to 6 feet 5 inches. Associated with the remains, besides the shoes, were a rusty jack knife, long underwear pants, and a T-shirt. DNA testing was requested. So was botanical testing on roots intertwined with the bones. However, the best lead for identification is the T-shirt; it was imprinted with "Before I started working here I drank, smoked, and used foul language for no reason at all. But thanks to this job, I now have a reason."<ref name=shoe2>{{cite news|last1=Williams|first1=Linda|title=Detectives hope items from the grave help identify John Doe
|url=http://www.willitsnews.com/general-news/20130321/detectives-hope-items-from-the-grave-help-identify-john-doe|accessdate=24 July 2016|work=Willits News|date=21 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=shoe3>{{cite news|last1=Revelle|first1=Tiffany|title=MCSO seeking public's help to identify remains found in Piercy
|url=http://www.ukiahdailyjournal.com/lifestyle/20130322/mcso-seeking-publics-help-to-identify-remains-found-in-piercy|accessdate=24 July 2016|work=Ukiah Daily Journal|date=22 March 2013}}</ref>

