{{For|the later ruler of Albania with the same name|Louis of Évreux, Duke of Durazzo}}
[[File:Armoiries Anjou Durazzo.png|125px|right|thumb|Coat of arms of Louis of Durazzo.]]

'''Louis of Durazzo''' (1324 – 22 July 1362) was [[Count of Gravina]] and [[Morrone]]. He was the son of [[John of Gravina]] and [[Agnes of Périgord]].{{sfn|Zacour|1960|p=32}}

In 1337, he was named Vicar- and Captain-General of the [[Kingdom of Albania (medieval)|Kingdom of Albania]]. During the ascension of the Durazzeschi at the court of [[Kingdom of Naples|Naples]] during the reign of [[Joanna I of Naples|Joanna I]], he was one of the royal ambassadors to the [[Roman Curia]]. Upon the invasion of [[Louis I of Hungary]] and the execution of his elder brother, [[Charles, Duke of Durazzo]], in 1348, he was imprisoned, with his younger brother [[Robert of Durazzo]], until 1352. The rest of his life was spent stirring up revolts against Joanna in [[Apulia]] with the aid of some [[Free Companies|Free Companions]]. These were ultimately quashed in 1360 by [[Louis of Taranto]], and Louis of Durazzo was imprisoned in the [[Castel dell'Ovo]] in Naples and murdered by poison.

==Family==
He married Margaret of Sanseverino in 1343, by whom he had three children:{{sfn|Casteen|2015|p=iii}}
# Louis (1344&ndash;d. young)
# [[Charles III of Naples]] (1345&ndash;1386){{sfn|Zacour|1960|p=32}}
# Agnes (1347&ndash;d. young)

